00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:43.000
So who are the people that work within the data science and advanced analytics group?

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:47.000
So our team is actually made up of four different teams.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So we have a data integration and governance team.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So they are the ones who will take the data and will connect to the database,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:03.000
transform the data in a way that is amenable for data science.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:06.000
And then we have the advanced analytics team.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:11.000
So they're the ones who are taking the data and building a model on top of it.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
And next we have the product development team.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So they're the ones who are deploying the model.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.000
So they're also the ones that are handling any kind of like downstream integrations.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So, for example, if you have a model that is supposed to send a push notification,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:31.000
the product development team will be the ones who are taking care of that.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And finally, we have the support team who are really the glue that hold everything together.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:44.000
So they're the ones who take care of project management and coordination at both an internal and external level.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.000
So because we're collaborating with lots of different groups within the hospital,

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:53.000
this is where having the support team is really helpful.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:57.000
Okay, so I briefly talked about some of the different solutions that we worked on.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:06.000
I want to kind of dive in and focus on one solution in particular, which is a successful deployment known as ChartWatch.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:13.000
So in August 2020, we deployed ChartWatch, which is an early warning system for detecting patient deterioration.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:19.000
So it's been running since August 2020. And to this day, it's still running in the hospital.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:25.000
ChartWatch was deployed to the general internal medicine ward within the hospital.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:31.000
I guess, as an aside, why is it called ChartWatch? Really, it's a branding thing.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:39.000
So before becoming known as CSAA, we were actually known as Chart, which is the Center for Healthcare Analytics Research and Training.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:45.000
So one thing you may notice throughout the talk is like I do mention a thing known as Chart,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:51.000
and it's really because of who we were initially known as.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So we developed ChartWatch. It's an early warning system.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And really, it's a model that predicts which patients are at risk of deterioration.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
So what I mean by deterioration is any of the following.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:13.000
So either transfer to the intensive care unit or ICU, death in the hospital, or transfer to the palliative care unit.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:20.000
So the way that the ChartWatch model was trained is it was trained on about 20,000 patient visits.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:27.000
And these data consisted of laboratory values, vital measurements and demographics.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:32.000
So these are all things that you would typically find in an electronic health record.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:39.000
And the way the model works is it outputs a risk group. So for every patient, you would generate a risk group.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:46.000
So the patient will be classified as either being high risk versus medium risk versus low risk.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:51.000
And then these risk groups are then delivered to different end users.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And you have different methods of delivery based on who the predictions are going out to.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:04.000
So, for example, we have emails. These are sent to our charge nurses, our palliative care team.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:11.000
And what these emails contain is basically a list of patients with their risk group listed.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:20.000
So if you look at the column, the third column from the right, you'll see the ChartWatch risk groups are included here.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
Another method of delivery is updates to the front end tool.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:31.000
So here we have a screenshot of our electronic sign up tool, which is typically used by clinicians.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And if you'll notice here, the screenshot has a column for ChartWatch.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:42.000
So once again, the third column from the right, you'll notice there is a ChartWatch column and this contains the ChartWatch risk groups.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And in this case, the risk groups have been color coded. So high risk group color coded as red, low risk group as green and the medium risk group as yellow.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:57.000
So we're following the traffic light system in this case.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And then finally, the last method of delivery is alerts that are sent to phones.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:13.000
So for patients that are flagged as high risk, we actually sent out an alert to clinician phones to let them know that the patient is at a high risk of deterioration.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:27.000
So going through the different methods of delivery, really, they're varying the level of urgency based off the end users that they're going to and based off the information that's being communicated.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:34.000
And you can read more about it in these links below. The slides will be available to share and you'll be able to access these links.

