OK, so I've gone over ChartWatch, but I have this slide just to really pause, take a step back and reflect on how we got from where we were to where we are now.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.000
I should probably title this slide back to the past because we are going to the past.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:15.000
So just to give a bit of context, this is where things were at before. So before we had scripts that were running from one person's laptop.

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:25.000
It works, but lots of ways in which this can fail. So, you know, what if this person is sick? What if they go on vacation?

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:33.000
Most of the laptops we use are Windows laptops. What if we get that Windows update? You know, like the laptop will be out for a while.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:42.000
We have no logging. We have no development environments. That's how things are before.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:50.000
Now, where things are at now. Well, you know, things are much better. We have service accounts. So basically, this removes the reliance on one person.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:58.000
We log all the things. We have staging versus production environments and so much more.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:03.000
So how do we get from before to now?

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:17.000
I'd say really it's a combination of hard work, trial and error, lots of talking, talking to the right people, figuring out what works and also what doesn't work.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:28.000
And I'd say out of all the tools and findings, I think we can summarize them into two categories. So we have the tools for development and also the tools for deployment.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
So let's dive right in. What do you need for development?

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:38.000
So the first thing that we need for development is really connections to databases.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:47.000
So within the hospital, there are various data systems. So, for example, we have a different system for labs, a different one for surgical procedures and so on.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:54.000
So in order to help the data science team work better, we developed a package called ChartDB.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.000
So ChartDB is an internal R package to interact with hospital databases.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:08.000
And with regards to connecting to databases, we wrote a bunch of connection functions and they all follow the same pattern.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:15.000
So, for example, if I want to connect to database A, I just need to give us input, my username and my password.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:20.000
If I want to connect to database B, I also give us input, my username and my password.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:32.000
And if I want to connect to the hospital's enterprise data warehouse, or rather the EDW, I would give, as you expect, my username and my password as input to the function.

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:43.000
So internally, this is actually what's happening. Internally, we have a bunch of retries because, you know, the connection may not work the very first time.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:53.000
We also have a bunch of checks, so making sure that the connection is successful and that what's being returned is what you expect.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:15:00.000
So ChartDB offers connection functions and it also offers other utility functions.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:09.000
So, for example, I have this get patient ADT function right here. And what ADT stands for is Admit Discharge Transfer.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:17.000
So, basically, when I call this function, it will return a list of patient movement events.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:29.000
So I have a row for when the patient first gets admitted to the hospital, when they transfer, for example, from the emergency department to a medical ward, and then when they get transferred.

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:34.000
And, you know, knowing where a patient is located in the hospital is pretty useful in nearly all of our projects.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:43.000
All right, so we have database connections. Another thing that we need for development is an environment that lets multiple people collaborate on projects.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:47.000
A really reproducible development environment.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:16:00.000
So in order to help with that, we ended up using RNs. Here I have a link to RNs and here's a screenshot of the documentation.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.000
As I said before, at the end, all of the links will be included in the slides.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
So RNs is an R package for R dependency management.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:19.000
And how are we using our project? Well, here's an example of our project structure.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:24.000
So, you know, we have our main folder, we have a bunch of files, a bunch of subfolders.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:33.000
And really, I want to bring attention to that last file at the end, which is the RNs.log file, which is where all of the RNs magic happens.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:45.000
So this is what the RNs.log file looks like. And basically what it does is it specifies the different packages that your project relies on, as well as the different package versions.

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:53.000
So, for example, here, my project relies on deep IR and I'm using version 1.0.7.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:08.000
So, you know, I could then give this RNs.log file to a teammate and then they can then ensure they're downloading the same packages as all the same package versions to contribute on the project.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:19.000
Okay, so I've highlighted a few things for development. So I have my database connections, I have my reproducible environment, which is facilitated through RNs.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:27.000
Another thing that I need is functions and utilities that are reused. So really what I mean by that is package-based development.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:38.000
So here I have a link to the R packages textbook, as well as a screenshot of documentation. I highly recommend it.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:54.000
So really, why write a package? There are a bunch of reasons, but I'd say that for us specifically, what we found the most relevant was being able to share code and knowledge with others, as well as having no more copy-pasting.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:06.000
So I find that as I'm developing, if I'm copy-pasting the same bit of code over and over, kind of like, you know, it rings an alarm. You're like, maybe I should take a step back and think of what I'm doing.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:18.000
So if we revisit the project structure that I introduced a few slides ago, this R subfolder right here is where you have all of your package functions.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:25.000
And then there is the description file right here, which is where you would define the attributes of your package.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:39.000
So for example, this is a description file that I have for ChartWatch. So, you know, it's listing out a bunch of attributes like the package name right here. So it's ChartWatch. The package version 1.11.10.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:49.000
And at the very end, I have the imports right here, which specifies the packages that my package relies on. So the dependencies.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:19:02.000
Okay, so our development checklist is, we're adding more to it. So we have our database connections. We have an environment that allows multiple people to collaborate. We have package-based development.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Another thing I'm going to add is environments, environments, environments. So the reason I say the same word three times is because we actually work with three different environments.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:17.000
We have the development environment, the staging environment, and the production environment.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:27.000
So the development environment, this could be your local computer. But in our cases, we usually use a development server.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:36.000
So what our development server includes is GPUs, which allow for any projects that require deep learning.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:53.000
And also, the development server works nicely with ChartDB. So that means that anyone who wants to develop something, you know, they're guaranteed that database connections will work for them. So they'll be able to access the data that they need for their projects.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:20:09.000
Next, you have the staging environment, which is as close to the real deployment environment as possible. So for example, when we need to make updates to ChartWatch, we would first apply it to the staging environment to make sure everything is working as we expect it.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:16.000
And then finally, there's a production environment, which is where things actually get deployed.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:33.000
All right, so things I need for development. The last thing I added was a thing about environments. Briefly talk about the production environment, which I think segues nicely into the next point, which is what do you need for deployment?

