00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:00.000
So, with that being said, what are the things that you need for deployment?

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:05.000
So, the first thing that we really need for deployment is authentication.

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:13.000
So, all of our deployed applications run on RStudio Connect, which is actually now PositConnect.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:19.000
So, one of the nice things about PositConnect is that it interacts with the hospital's active directory.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:24.000
So, what this means is that users can authenticate using their hospital username and password.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:29.000
So, for the developer, you know, we don't need to keep track of an extra server username and password.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:36.000
And then for the end users, in order to access applications, they could just log in with their hospital credentials.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:44.000
And a nice thing about being able to interact with active directory is that we can just use the existing groups to manage permissions.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:52.000
So, for example, if I have an application that I only want to give access to the SAA, so like the data science group,

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:56.000
I could just use the existing active directory group to enable that.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:04.000
Another thing that RStudio Connect, or rather PositConnect, allows us to do is to schedule scripts.

00:34:04.000 --> 00:34:13.000
So, we run our applications from service accounts, which is basically a non-user account in which we can run automated services.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:22.000
And it's this combination of automatic scheduling and using a service account that really makes it so that deployments don't rely on one person.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:33.000
So, you know, this is how things were before we had this cron job, which would call different bash scripts, which would then call different Python or R scripts.

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:46.000
But now that we're using PositConnect, we can leverage a lot of different things.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:52.000
Sorry, the screenshot is a bit small, so I listed all the different things, all the different tabs on the side.

00:34:52.000 --> 00:35:02.000
So, you know, we have the application information, we have the access tab, which is what we use to specify, for example, who can access a specific dashboard.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:06.000
We have the runtime settings, we have the scheduling settings.

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:11.000
So, scheduling settings is what we use to schedule our scripts.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:16.000
And then there's the tags, really for organizational purposes.

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:24.000
So, for example, all the ChartWatch scripts would get tagged as being ChartWatch environment variables and logs.

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.000
So, we're adding a few things for deployment.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:30.000
We have authentication, we have scheduling.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:35.000
Another thing that's useful for deployment is being able to know when there's a downtime.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:45.000
So, for example, here, this is a screenshot of one of our Slack channels where, you know, we received an alert, you know, ChartWatch is down, for example.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:54.000
So, in order to enable this, we created Jarvis, which is an R package for helping us monitor our production applications.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:36:02.000
So, Jarvis is the IRONMAN's robot assistant.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:06.000
Yeah, that's where the package name came from.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:11.000
Yeah, so we use Jarvis for a few notifications.

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
So, we can use it to send email alerts.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:20.000
So, in this example here, you know, Jarvis sent email letting me know that there's an issue with the COVID dashboard.

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:26.000
As shown previously, we can use Jarvis to send Slack messages, like here.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:31.000
And we also use Jarvis to check the health of systems that we depend on.

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:40.000
So, for example, if you want to check a specific database, right, I can check that my connection to the enterprise data warehouse still works.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:46.000
And I can also check that I can access different file systems with Jarvis.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:56.000
So, on top of using Jarvis for different notifications, we also developed a few downtime protocols, which are pretty project specific.

00:36:56.000 --> 00:37:07.000
So, for example, with ChartWatch, if ever there's something that goes down, we would send this kind of email to the hospital, to all the hospital users.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:11.000
So, we have a specific email template that we use here.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:15.000
And this email template actually follows the one that IT uses.

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:23.000
So, you know, it's color coded at the top where, you know, red is for unplanned downtime, blue is for planned downtime, and so on.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:27.000
There's a list of things that we need to specify.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:31.000
And this will go out to all the hospital users.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:35.000
So, like, not all projects will require something like this.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:42.000
But something like ChartWatch, which is embedded into clinical care, does require something a bit more robust.

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:49.000
Basically, like, when things go down with ChartWatch, it's not just the DSA team that needs to be notified.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:53.000
It's other people within the hospital.

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:58.000
All right, so you have authentication, scheduling, downtime.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:06.000
I'd say another thing that you need for the deployment is a secure way to download internally developed packages.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:10.000
I think I need to expand on this a bit more.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:22.000
So, to give a bit of context, around the holiday time last year, we started seeing these kinds of messages in our Slack channels.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:28.000
So, you know, like, not able to receive emails, you know, check log4j.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:34.000
Sorry, running late because I was on a meeting with IT because of log4j.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:40.000
If you use PyCharm, be careful. There's a log4j file in there.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:45.000
I found log4j files in my VS Code folder.

00:38:45.000 --> 00:38:48.000
There's something going on with log4j.

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:52.000
The log4j, for those who don't know, it's a Java-based logging utility.

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:58.000
And in December 2021, there was the log4j flaw.

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:05.000
And basically what happened is this could allow malicious users to access internal networks.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:13.000
And I guess just to highlight the severity of the log4j flaw, like, here are some headlines that were coming out around that time.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:23.000
So log4j is a pervasive vulnerability. Update your devices now. A hole in a popular piece of code is an open window for criminals.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:31.000
The log4j software flaw is endemic, according to the Cyber Safety Panel.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:40.000
So really, this whole thing about log4j is to motivate the next point is that we need to limit who can access the hospital network.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:44.000
And this is where something like Posit Package Manager comes in.

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:52.000
So Posit Package Manager, also formally RStudio Package Manager, is a repository management server.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:59.000
And what it allows us to do is download packages while being disconnected from the Internet.

00:39:59.000 --> 00:40:10.000
So if I go back to rm, which I mentioned a few slides ago, remember we had our rm.log file, which specifies the different packages and versions.

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:14.000
So here it specifies how the package is being downloaded.

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:29.000
So instead of being downloaded from, say, GitHub or from CRAN, we're downloading from RSTM, which stands for RStudio Package Manager, which is also Posit Package Manager.

00:40:29.000 --> 00:40:36.000
So a few more things that we've added for deployment. So we just added a secure way to download internally developed packages.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:40.000
One more thing I want to add is an implementation plan.

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:48.000
So, so far, all the things that we've discussed previously, I guess you can apply to data science in general.

00:40:48.000 --> 00:41:00.000
For this implementation plan, it's probably a bit more focused on the health care setting and on deploying within the hospital.

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:06.000
So just to recap how ChartWatch is delivering predictions, they're going to different end users.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:11.000
So we have our emails that are going to charge nurses, the palliative care team.

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:17.000
We're updating this electronic sign out front end tool that clinicians access.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:21.000
We're sending alerts whenever there's a patient that's flagged as high risk.

00:41:21.000 --> 00:41:30.000
This is going directly to clinician phones. And really, if you like, just looking at the way things are delivered, there's a lot of people involved.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:39.000
So you have like your church nurses, your palliative care team, you have I.T., you have residents and physicians.

00:41:39.000 --> 00:41:47.000
And it's with that in mind that when we when we came up with what we put together, the implementation team,

00:41:47.000 --> 00:41:55.000
we wanted to make sure that people from all of these different end user groups are being represented and included in these implementation team meetings.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:42:02.000
Right. So we made sure we had people from general internal medicine, from the intensive care unit, from palliative care,

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:09.000
from clinical informatics, from I.T. and then like from the data science team.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:13.000
Just want to highlight that collaboration is really important here.

00:42:13.000 --> 00:42:18.000
And also the whole idea for ChartWatch actually came from a general internal medicine doctor.

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:31.000
So they were the ones that are leading the project throughout the whole course and really making sure we were going from development all the way to deployment.

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:38.000
So one of the things that the implementation team was tasked with doing was coming up with an intervention.

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:44.000
So after ChartWatch flags a patient as being high risk, what happens then?

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:50.000
So the implementation team develop a clinical workflow.

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:57.000
This is a clinical workflow looks like. I won't go into too much detail, but I will point out a few things.

00:42:57.000 --> 00:43:04.000
So, you know, when a patient is flagged as being high risk by ChartWatch, there are a few things that need to happen after that.

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:10.000
So one of them is placing orders to increase vital sign measurements, reviewing recent labs,

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:14.000
reviewing recent medications and recent imaging orders.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:23.000
And really all the things that you find in this clinical workflow are all things that a clinician would normally do if they suspected a patient of deteriorating.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:27.000
So when developing this, this checklist, this clinical workflow,

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:34.000
it was really important to make sure that it wasn't disrupting any existing processes.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:42.000
So you want to consider existing resources. You don't want to reimplement a workflow that already exists, for example.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:46.000
And also the alerting notifications all fit within existing processes.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:51.000
So, for example, when it came to the timing of emails,

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:56.000
some of the emails that we sent out is sent to the charge nurse and this email is sent out twice a day.

00:43:56.000 --> 00:44:01.000
And they're sent at a time that makes the most sense with how the shifts work.

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:08.000
So once again, we don't want to disrupt how things are working currently.

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:13.000
And with regards to the clinical pathway, really ensuring that there are time targets.

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:18.000
So, for example, after ChartWatch flags a patient as being high risk,

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:25.000
one of the things that the clinicians must do is increase number of vital measurements within 24 hours of the alert being sent.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:35.000
So having this 24 hour time target makes it that we can then go into the electronic health record and then measure whether or not this is happening.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:40.000
And, of course, leaving room for clinical judgment.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:46.000
And so when working on the implementation plan, we include a signed deployment period.

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:53.000
So basically, this is where your entire pipeline is running, but the final outputs are silenced.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:45:04.000
This is useful for identifying bugs and addressing unexpected changes, such as change to how the Troponin lab test is done.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:12.000
So the Troponin test is one that's commonly used to diagnose heart attacks and other heart related problems.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:19.000
So during the deployment of ChartWatch, like the way this is measured got changed.

00:45:19.000 --> 00:45:27.000
And this is something that we have to address. So we have to address that in our data extraction code and also in our data processing code.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:31.000
Other changes that can happen can be due to deploying at the beginning of the pandemic.

00:45:31.000 --> 00:45:40.000
So, you know, during that time, there's lots of rooms that are being made available or unavailable based off, you know, the patients are testing positive for COVID.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:46.000
Patients are being moved to completely different units in the hospital just based on capacity.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:51.000
So this has to be addressed in our data extraction code.

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:56.000
Another thing that the signed deployment period was useful for was for catching bugs.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:01.000
This is a really interesting bug that we encountered.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:07.000
I'm guessing that most people that are watching this talk are R users.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:18.000
So, you know, I can ask the following question, how are missing values represented in R?

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:28.000
So I think most of you know it's an R missing values are represented as MA, which means unavailable.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:35.000
Now, next question is, what's the chemical element for sodium?

00:46:35.000 --> 00:46:39.000
I think some of you can see where this is going.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:45.000
So the chemical element for sodium is also MA.

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:52.000
So we work in the hospital. In the hospital, there are blood tests that are done.

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:56.000
And, you know, one of the things that gets measured in blood tests is sodium.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:03.000
So when we silently deployed ChartWatch, we noticed that there were no sodium tests that were being measured.

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:08.000
This is an example. This is a graph that shows kind of all the electrolyte counts.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:14.000
So in blue is sodium. And if you notice here, the blue is set to zero.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:18.000
OK, like this doesn't seem right. Like what's going on?

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:30.000
So when you went and checked the code, what we found was that the R code that we were using to read some of the lab's data was interpreting all of the sodium tests as being MA not available.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:34.000
So yeah, this is what happened. The fix was actually pretty straightforward.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:41.000
It was just like updating one of the function parameters to not read MA as not available.

00:47:41.000 --> 00:47:49.000
It was just a very interesting bug that we ran into.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:54.000
So once we were done with the sign period, it's time to go live.

00:47:54.000 --> 00:48:02.000
So actually for us, we had a pilot phase in which we first deployed to two general internal medicine teams only.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:11.000
And during that time, we had weekly meetings which were used to debug any issues we ran into, go over the patients that were flagged by ChartWatch,

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:16.000
you know, check like, does it make sense or is there anything weird or unexpected?

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:21.000
So that was the approach that we took for going live.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:28.000
And then we really did in a phased approach to start off with two teams and deploy to the rest of the teams.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:39.000
And really throughout this whole process, so throughout the pilot phase, throughout deployment, throughout, you know, developing the clinical workflow and user engagement is important.

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:44.000
This is not something that could have been possible with just a data science team.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:57.000
So when it came to developing the clinical pathway, we really relied on the general internal medicine team, on the palliative care team, on the nurses we were working with to develop that pathway.

00:48:57.000 --> 00:49:06.000
And also when it came to developing education and training processes, that was, once again, a highly collaborative effort.

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:12.000
So yeah, so things need for deployment, implementation plan, super important.

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:20.000
One last thing that I will mention for deployment is something about monitoring.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:29.000
There's a question mark here because, you know, this could be a whole talk and we're already nearing the end of this talk.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:34.000
So it is a whole talk. There's plenty of other people that have spoken about monitoring.

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:39.000
So I would redirect you to watch these amazing talks. Lots of great insights.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:45.000
With the time remaining, I will mention a few things specific to chart watch, though.

00:49:45.000 --> 00:49:51.000
So a chart watch, one of the things that we want to look at is model performance.

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:56.000
But that's a bit hard to do once the model has been deployed.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:50:06.000
Let me expound on that a bit more.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:10.000
Hmm. Somehow we got kicked out there, but here you are.

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:11.000
Am I still here?

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
It was just for a second. Yep.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:16.000
OK. All good?

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:18.000
Yep, we're good.

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:27.000
OK, so we just backtrack a bit. So with chart watch, one of the things that we want to look at is model performance.

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:31.000
But that is difficult to do once the model has been deployed.

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:39.000
So clinicians, one of the things that they asked for was a target positive predictive value of 0.33.

00:50:39.000 --> 00:50:46.000
So what this means is that for every three alarms, at least one of them should be correct.

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:52.000
But that is kind of hard to measure once you are deployed and in production.

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:59.000
So what I mean by that is, let's say chart watch flags a patient as being high risk and sends out an alarm.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:04.000
And then that patient doesn't deteriorate like they don't transfer to the ICU.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:10.000
They don't die. Does that mean that the chart watch prediction was incorrect?

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:14.000
Or does that mean that the chart watch prediction was correct?

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:22.000
And then because clinicians received that alert, they were able to intervene and prevent that outcome from happening.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:28.000
So, yeah, in deployment, we we get these cases where there are these false alarms,

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:41.000
which we're not sure if they're actually false alarms or if they're averted outcomes just based off this successful intervention.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:47.000
Yes. Another thing we measure in chart watch is the daily number of alerts.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:53.000
So on average, we're sending two alerts per day, which is a reasonable number that the clinicians are happy with.

00:51:53.000 --> 00:51:57.000
There are some days where there are no alerts and there are some days where there are lots of alerts.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:04.000
So, for example, I think there's like nine or eight alerts sometime in like April or May.

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:11.000
So, yeah, one of the things that we were really concerned with was make sure there weren't too many alerts.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:16.000
So we worked with the clinicians to ensure that we were minimizing alerts.

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:23.000
So right now, the way things work is that, you know, a patient will receive an alert if chart watch classifies them as being high risk.

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:31.000
We added some additional rules on top of that. And those rules we develop with the help of the end users.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:36.000
So, you know, we don't re-alert a patient unless it's been 48 hours since their previous alert.

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:41.000
You know, this just ensure that we're not alerting for the same patient every hour, for example.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:49.000
And we added this additional rule, which is that we don't alert a patient if they just came from the intensive care unit.

00:52:49.000 --> 00:52:55.000
Because if a patient is coming from the ICU, you know, like the clinicians already know that they may not be doing too well.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:53:07.000
And it's expected that, you know, their vital measurements, their labs might be looking a little off because they just came from intensive care.

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:12.000
The last thing I will say about monitoring is regarding clinical adherence.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:21.000
So how do we know that when a patient receives a chart watch alert, the clinician is actually doing something and they're not just ignoring that alert?

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:27.000
So one of the things that we look at is the number of vitals that are measured after an alert is sent.

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:31.000
So we do that because as part of the clinical workflow,

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:38.000
one of the things that the clinicians have to do when they receive a chart watch alert is increase the number of vital measurements.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:43.000
This is something that we can easily measure just by looking at the electronic health care record,

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:50.000
looking at the number of vitals that are sent after an alert has been sent.

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:59.000
I mean, it's not a perfect measure because the number of vitals can increase for reasons unrelated to chart watch,

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:09.000
but it's a proxy and it gives us a good enough idea of clinical adherence.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:15.000
So this brings us towards the end of our talk. So let me just summarize some of the things that we talked about.

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:21.000
So we looked at the different tools for development and deployment of an early warning system in the hospital.

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:26.000
And so on the development side, the things that we found useful were database connections,

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:33.000
reproducible environment facilitated through RNs, package based development,

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:37.000
the different development staging and production environments.

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:44.000
And then on the deployment side, we had authentication and scheduling, which were facilitated by Posit Connect.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:53.000
We had downtime protocols, a secure way to download internally developed packages with the help of Posit Package Manager.

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:59.000
We had an implementation plan in which we're working with our different collaborators, our end users.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:09.000
And then we had monitoring at the very end. And, you know, all of this would not have been possible if it weren't for collaboration.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:14.000
I think it's something I keep saying throughout the talks that collaboration is really important.

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:19.000
Developing and deploying chart watch in the hospital is not something that we could have done on our own.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:28.000
I was really by working with a great team and a lot of different people within the hospital that this was possible.

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:33.000
